{{Unreferenced|date=January 2007}}

'''Parry Aftab''' is a [[lawyer]]<ref>http://www.wiredsafety.org/resources/biographies/parry/index.html</ref> who specializes in online safety. She is the Executive Director of WiredSafety.org, a volunteer organization dedicated to online safety. Aftab shut down her law practice in 2000 to pursue her charitable activities.

Her areas of legal expertise are Children Online, Worldwide Cybercrime Protection and Prevention, Privacy, Data Collection and Security, Workplace Risk Management and Security, Consumer Protection, Advertising and the Internet, E-Commerce, Cyberstalking and Harassment, Child Exploitation and Child Pornography. She also works with members of the Internet industry to help build safer products and services.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

She is The Privacy Lawyer columnist for Information Week Magazine and consults for various news outlets.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

== Education ==

*City University of New York, BA, 1981
*Hunter College, Valedictorian, Phi Beta Kappa (Nu Chapter)
*New York University School of Law, JD, 1984

== Consulting and advisory activities ==

She consults for and works with law enforcement agencies, worldwide, on cybercrime prevention, 
cyber-terrorism, law enforcement and security matters.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}  She has worked with FBI, U.S. Customs, Interpol, Scotland Yard, the Home Office, Tokyo Metropolitan Police and Japan's National Police, Hong Kong Police and the RCMP.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

Parry is a regular source to media outlets worldwide on Internet privacy, marketing, advertising and regulatory issues, as well as children and online safety and security.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}  She has been quoted or featured in magazines such as Newsweek, U.S News & World Report, Family Circle, Good Housekeeping, Reader's Digest, Better Homes and Gardens, Information Weekly, Teen People, Ladies Home Journal, Smart Business Magazine, The London Times Magazine, New York Magazine, Cosmopolitan Magazine. {{Fact|date=February 2007}}

She has been consulted by local news publications and has appeared as a commentator on international, national, and local television news programs.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

She has been providing public service safety information for many years.{{Fact|date=February 2007}} Parry provides parent Internet education and online safety content for such sites as Children's Television  Workshop, Disney, Microsoft, Oracle, Verizon, AT&T and MSNBC and many of the social networking sites.{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 

Her online discussions and writing are have been published and quoted by legal journals in articles and judges in their decisions.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

==Katie.com==

{{main|Katie.com}}

Aftab was involved in a dispute surrounding the domain [[katie.com]] between 2000 and 2004. In 2000, [[Penguin Group|Penguin Putnam]] had planned to release a book titled ''Katie.com''; the domain was owned by [[Katie Jones (web entrepreneur)|Katie Jones]], which resulted in a dispute between her and the publisher.<ref name = "penguin">{{cite news
| last = Sheriff
| first = Lucy
| title = Penguin backs down on Katie.com
| url = http://www.theregister.co.uk/2004/08/09/penguin_renames_katie_book/
| date = 2004-08-09
| accessdate = 2007-01-30}}</ref>
During the dispute, Aftab contacted Jones and attempted to persuade Jones to hand over the site. When Jones refused, Aftab accused her of having a hidden agenda, which Jones considered to be cyberbullying in itself.<ref name = "host">{{cite news
| last = Sheriff
| first = Lucy
| title = Katie.com lawyer to host cyber-bullying conference
| url = http://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/01/19/cyber_bully/
| date = 2005-01-19
| accessdate = 2007-01-30}}</ref>
In an interview, Jones stated that she was being emotionally blackmailed and that Aftab told her that "things would only get worse [for Jones]" if she did not hand over the domain.<ref name = "interview">{{cite web
| last = E. Rustad Jr.
| first = Roger
| title = Interview with Katie Jones of (the Real) Katie.com
| url = http://grep.law.harvard.edu/articles/04/08/06/033216.shtml
| accessdate = 2007-01-30}}</ref>
Jones received massive support from the online community,<ref name = "interview"/><ref name = "penguin"/> and eventually Penguin renamed the book ''A Girl's Life Online''.

== Selected honors ==

*Woman of the Year, 2004, Child Abuse Prevention Services{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 
*Activist of the Year Award, 2002 Awarded by Media Ecology Association{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 
*Internet Pioneer of the Year, 2001 Awarded by Family PC Magazine{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 
*Home Office, UK Child Protection, Criminal Laws and Law Enforcement Task Forces{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 
*Singapore Broadcasting Authority, PAGi advisory and founder of Cybermums and Dads{{Fact|date=February 2007}} 

== Organizations ==

*The Internet Society Elected Chair, Internet Societal Task Force and Societal Steering Group (worldwide, 2001) 
*Member of Public Policy Committee ISOC (2001-present) 
*Chair, Privacy and Security Working Group of The Internet Society Task Force (2000-2001)appointed member since 1999
*WiredSafety ([http://www.wiredsafety.org]) the world's largest Internet safety and help group, formerly functioned as Cyberangels, recipient of President's Service Award, 1998, Executive Director (1998-present)
*Wired Kids ([http://www.wiredkids.org]) Executive Director (1999-present)
*Ad Council Advisory Committee member (1999 - present)
*Cyberlawenforcement ([http://www.cyberlawenforcement.com]) the group for law enforcement volunteers and networks on cybercrime investigations, training and prevention Executive Director (2000-present)
*UNESCO President, US National Action Committee, Innocence in Danger (1998-present)
*[http://www.k9angels.org/ K-9 Angels] a September 11th relief program for search and rescue dogs, Executive Director (2001-present)
*Children's Television Workshop Online (Sesame Workshop) Advisory Board (1998 - present)
*The National Urban League Technology Advisory Committee (1997 - present)
*New York State Bar Association Committee on Internet and Litigation of the Commercial and Federal Litigation Section

== Publications and related activities ==
She has written the books ''The Parent's Guide to Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace'' (McGraw-Hill, January 2000) and ''A Parents' Guide to the Internet'' (SC Press, October 1997).

Aftab has contributed to the books ''Child Abuse on the Internet.... Ending the Silence'' (2001, editor Carlos A. Arnaldo), ''The Technical Response: Blocking, Filtering And Rating The Internet'', ''The Best In E-Commerce Law'' (2001, Warren E.Agin), and was the editor of ''Children's Online Privacy Law''.

Her writings have been published in ''Information Week'', ''[[New York Law Journal]]'', ''Legal Times'', ''Preventive Law Reporter'', ''Working Women Magazine'', ''The Texas Lawyer'', ''Children's Legal Rights Law Journal'', ''New Jersey Law Journal'', and ''The Internet Lawyer''.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

Aftab has been featured in ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' (US edition), ''[[TV Guide]]'' (US edition), ''[[Biography Magazine]]'', ''[[New York Sunday Times]]'', and the ''[[International Herald Tribune]]''.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

==== Selected online activities ====

